title: For Sale:  CZ-82 9mm Makarov Milsurp Pistol
postcontent: Up for sale is my CZ-82 in 9mm Makarov.  This pistol is a fantastic double-stack makarov-style pistol made by the legendary CZ.  The pistol has a couple of interesting features. For example, it features polygonal rifling, which has a shaped bore, rather than one with noticable grooves, which increases the effective lifetime of the barrel and accuracy.  It also features a double-stack magazine, which was my original buying point for the pistol.  It's an all-steel contruction with a 12+1 capacity, a simple blow-back mechanism, and a safety.I used this pistol as a daily carry for a about a year and a half, and as such am selling it with a custom-built IWB holster from Kholster.  It's an all-holster with a plastic molded holding area for the pistol that was molded by my own gun, which cost about $80 to have made.  I'm also including a spare magazine and about 775 rounds of 9x18mm ammo for the gun as well.All in all, it's a great shooter with a nice slim profile that serves great as a daily carry, or a fun well-made Makarov on the range. Asking price is $450.

RARE SS192 “Green Ammo” was produced for ONLY 3 months before FN turned to the SS195LF. The SS192 "Green Ammo" is the predecessor to the current SS195LF which uses the same 27gr HP aluminum core bullet but with a lead free primer, hence the LF designation. The SS192 “green ammo” or environmentally friendly ammo was SS195LF ammo before they changed the name and box. The manufacture (FN Herstal) relates the labeling as a way to visibly mark the packaging so that there is a lower chance for this to be mixed up with SS192 ammunition that contains lead primer.

title: For Sale:  KelTec, P-3AT, .380 Semi Auto, 6+1, Blued/Black, NIB
postcontent: DEALER TRANSACTION Keel Mountain Munitions has available a KelTec, P-3AT, .380 Semi Auto, 6+1, Blued/Black, NIB. The P-3AT has five main component groups: barrel, slide, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 ordnance steel, heat treated to 48 HRC. The slide is also 4140 steel, and contains the firing pin and the extractor. The rectangular frame is machined from solid 7075-T6 aluminum and houses the firing mechanism. The trigger connects via a transfer bar to the hammer. The hammer is driven by a novel free floating extension spring. The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. After firing, the hammer block holds the hammer away from the firing pin, providing a mechanical safety.
